df = pd.read_csv('Food_Inspections.csv')    # Read the dataset downloaded from https://data.cityofchicago.org/Health-Human-Services/Food-Inspections/4ijn-s7e5
violations = df[df['Results'] == 'Fail']    # Select only the records corresponding to failed inspection
violations = violations.dropna(subset=['Violations'])   # Cleaning the data by removing null values under Violations column

print("Step 1.")
print("- Example of Violation before splitting by '|' : \n", violations[violations['Inspection ID'] == 52240]['Violations'].values)
violations['Reasons'] = violations['Violations'].apply(lambda x: re.split('\|\s', x))   # splitting the Violations by '|' and space 
print("- Example of Violation after splitting by '|' : \n", violations[violations['Inspection ID'] == 52240]['Reasons'].values)
print("\nThe violations were split by '|' and made into a list of violations.\n")

violations['Key'] = violations['License #'].astype(str) + '-' + violations['DBA Name'] + '-' + violations['Address'].astype(str) #Making a key of License #, DBA Name and Address to identify a unique business

reasons = violations[['Inspection ID', 'DBA Name', 'License #', 'Address', 'Key', 'Reasons', 'Inspection Date']].explode('Reasons') #Exploding the list of violations to a separate row
reasons = pd.DataFrame(reasons)

reasons['Code'] = reasons['Reasons'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r'^[\d]+', x))
reasons['Code'] = reasons['Code'].apply(lambda x: ''.join(map(str, x))).astype(int)

reasons['Comments'] = reasons['Reasons'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r'\d+\.\s*.*\s*-\s*Comments\:\s*(.*)', x, re.IGNORECASE))

print("Step 2.")
print("Picking out the Violation description from the violations. The description is between the violation code and Comments. Sometimes comments does not exist")
print("- Original violation before regex is applied (With Comments) :")
print(reasons['Reasons'].iloc[0])
print("- Original violation before regex is applied (Without Comments) :")
print(reasons[(reasons['Inspection ID'] == 2279241) & (reasons['Code'] == 25)]['Reasons'].values)
reasons['Reasons_modified'] = reasons['Reasons'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r'\d+\.\s*(.*?)(?=\s*(?:-*\s*Comments*))', x, re.IGNORECASE) if (re.findall(r'(Comments)', x, re.IGNORECASE)) else re.findall(r'\d+\.\s*(.*)$', x, re.IGNORECASE))
print("\n- Violation description after regex is applied (With Comments) :")
print(reasons['Reasons_modified'].iloc[0])
print("- Violation description after regex is applied (Without Comments) :")
print(reasons[(reasons['Inspection ID'] == 2279241) & (reasons['Code'] == 25)]['Reasons_modified'].values[0])

reasons['Reasons_modified'] = reasons['Reasons_modified'].apply(lambda x: x[0].rstrip())    # rstrip() to remove spaces at the end
reasons['Key'] = reasons['Key'].apply(lambda x: x.rstrip()) # rstrip() to remove spaces at the end
reasons['Key'] = reasons['Key'].apply(lambda x: x.upper())  # Change key to uppercase to ensure that case is ignored in the Key

r_final = reasons['Reasons_modified'].explode('Reasons_modified') # type: ignore (put this as VS Code highlights it red otherwise) 
r_final = pd.DataFrame(r_final.value_counts())  # Count the number of times a violation description occurs in the table

data = r_final.head(10) # Choosing the top 10 violations
print("\nStep 3.\n- The frequency of each violation is counted using value_counts() and top 10 most frequently occuring violations are visualized below.")

plt.grid(visible=False)

# To change a numbe from #### to #,### in the graph
def label_format(label_value):
    locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'en_US.UTF-8')
    return locale.format_string("%d", label_value, grouping=True)

ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0], labels=[label_format(x.get_width()) for x in ax.containers[0]], padding=5, fontsize=13)
plt.show()

#### Identifying Repeated Offenders ####
offenses = reasons.drop_duplicates(subset=['Inspection ID'], keep='first')  # Since there are instances where a violation description may repeat for a particular inspection, in order to find the number of establisments who are offenders, this is not required.
repeated_offenses = offenses[['Key', 'Inspection ID']].groupby(by=['Key']).count().reset_index()    # Group by to get the number of inspections for each unique business and specific violation description

# Data
total_offenders = len(repeated_offenses)
repeat_num = len(repeated_offenses[repeated_offenses['Inspection ID'] > 1]) # number of establisments that have more than one inspection are repeat offenders
nonrepeat_num = total_offenders - repeat_num    # number of establisments that have one inspection only are not repeat offenders

# Calculate percentages
repeat_pct = repeat_num / total_offenders * 100
nonrepeat_pct = 100 - repeat_pct

# Create a donut chart
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, figsize=(20, 4))
wedges, labels, _ = ax1.pie([repeat_num, nonrepeat_num], labels=['Repeat Offenders\n'+"("+str(label_format(repeat_num))+")", 'Non-Repeat Offenders\n'+"("+str(label_format(nonrepeat_num))+")"], 
                           colors=['#d11919', 'lightgray'], 
                           autopct=lambda pct: f"{pct:.0f}%", pctdistance=0.8,
                           startangle=90, counterclock=False, wedgeprops=dict(width=0.4, edgecolor='w'), textprops=dict(fontsize=9))

# Add a circle at the center to create a donut chart
centre_circle = plt.Circle((0,0),0.6,color='white', fc='white',linewidth=0)
fig.gca().add_artist(centre_circle)

# Add the total to the center of the chart
total_label = ax1.text(0, 0, f"{label_format(total_offenders)}\nTotal Offenders", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12)

# Add a title
ax1.set_title('BUSINESSES THAT ARE REPEAT AND NON-REPEATING OFFENDERS', fontsize=15)

# Add legend
ax1.legend(wedges, ['Repeat Offenders', 'Non-Repeat Offenders'], loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(0.85, 0.8), fontsize=10)

#### IDENTIFY IF THE REPEAT OFFENDERS HAVE REPEATING VIOLATIONS OR NOT ####

total_repeated_offenders = repeated_offenses[repeated_offenses['Inspection ID'] > 1]
total_repeated_offenders = total_repeated_offenders.rename({'Inspection ID': 'n_Inspections'}, axis=1)

df_1 = reasons.drop_duplicates(subset=['Inspection ID', 'Reasons_modified'], keep='first')
df_1 = df_1[['Key', 'Reasons_modified', 'Inspection ID']].groupby(by=['Key', 'Reasons_modified']).count().reset_index()
df_1 = df_1.rename(columns={'Inspection ID': 'Count_V'})

repeated_offenders = total_repeated_offenders[['Key', 'n_Inspections']].merge(df_1, how='right', on='Key')
repeated_offenders = repeated_offenders.dropna(subset=['n_Inspections'])

r_offenses_df = pd.DataFrame(repeated_offenders[repeated_offenders['Count_V'] > 1]['Key'].unique(), columns=['Key_offense'])
r_offenses = len(repeated_offenders[repeated_offenders['Count_V'] > 1]['Key'].unique())

tro = len(total_repeated_offenders)
nr_offenses = tro - r_offenses

# Calculate percentages
r_pct = r_offenses / tro * 100
nr_pct = 100 - r_pct

# Create a donut chart

wedges, labels, _ = ax2.pie([r_pct, nr_pct], labels=['Establishments having same violations\n'+"("+str(label_format(r_offenses))+")", 'Establishments having different violations\n'+"("+str(label_format(nr_offenses))+")"], 
                           colors=['#d11919', 'lightgray'], 
                           autopct=lambda pct: f"{pct:.0f}%", pctdistance=0.8,
                           startangle=90, counterclock=False, wedgeprops=dict(width=0.4, edgecolor='w'), textprops=dict(fontsize=9))

# Add a circle at the center to create a donut chart
centre_circle = plt.Circle((0,0),0.6,color='white', fc='white',linewidth=0)
fig.gca().add_artist(centre_circle)

# Add the total to the center of the chart
total_label = ax2.text(0, 0, f"{label_format(tro)}\nTotal Repeating\nOffenders", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12)

# Add a title
ax2.set_title('REPEATING OFFENDERS HAVING SAME/DIFFERENT VIOLATIONS ACROSS INSPECTIONS', fontsize=15)

# Add legend
ax2.legend(wedges, ['Establishments having same violations', 'Establishments having different violations'], loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(0.85, 0.8), fontsize=10)

# Display the chart
plt.show()
  1. The establishments that have more than one inspection ID are considered to be "Repeat Offenders" as they ae considered to have failed more than one inspection while those with just 1 inspection ID are considered "Non-repeating Offenders". As seen above, There are 21,048 establishments that have violations of which 49% of the businesses are repeating offenders, i.e; failed more than 1 inspection and the remaining are not.
  2. Of the 10,289 repeating offenders, in order to find if they have violations that have been repeated across inspections, the inspections that have the same violation with different comments present and to avoid duplicate count of repeated violations, the duplicates are dropped. The number for each violation description across inspections for a business are calculated and those that have violations more than 1 are considered to have that violation repeated in other inspections.
  3. Thus, 8,801 Establishments have same violations in their history.

df['Key'] = df['License #'].astype(str) + '-' + df['DBA Name'].astype(str) + '-' + df['Address'].astype(str)
df['Key'] = df['Key'].apply(lambda x: x.upper())
df['Key'] = df['Key'].apply(lambda x: x.strip())

out_of_business = df[df['Results'] == 'Out of Business']
ob = len(out_of_business['Key'].unique())
df_ob = df[df['Key'].isin(out_of_business['Key'].to_list())]
df_ob = df_ob[df_ob['Results'] != 'Out of Business']

df_ob = df_ob[['Key', 'Violations']].groupby(by=['Key', 'Violations']).count().reset_index()
df_ob_l = len(df_ob['Key'].unique())

no_history = ob - df_ob_l

# Calculate percentages
ob_pct = df_ob_l / ob * 100
n_pct = 100 - ob_pct

# Create a donut chart
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 4))

There are a total of 20,980 establishments out of business. These establishments were then cecked against the entire dataset to see if they had any violations present before they were closed down. If the number of violations is more than 0 they had a violation This is excluding the instance declaring they went Out of business as it is taking a look at the prior history only.

  • The top 4 reasons (given in order in the legend) seem to follow a similar trend of increase in around 2011, drop in 2012 to around 2015 and then rising to significantly to drop in 2018. This is most likely due to the fact that these are no longer used after 2018 and have been modified to change their scope.
  • The violation "PHYSICAL FACILITIES INSTALLED, MAINTAINED & CLEAN" was not in use till 2018 and was introduced after. It can be seen to have the highest peak amongst all the violation throughout the years at 2019 and a second higher peak in 2022. There's a significant drop after this most likely as data is very less for the year ongoing year 2023.
